==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Satire
<hw>Sat"ire</hw> <pr>(?; <xex>in Eng. often</xex> <?/; 277)</pr>,
<pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>satira</ets>, <ets>satura</ets>, fr.
<ets>satura</ets> (sc. <ets>lanx</ets>) a dish filled with various kinds
of fruits, food composed of various ingredients, a mixture, a medley,
fr. <ets>satur</ets> full of food, sated, fr. <ets>sat</ets>,
<ets>satis</ets>, enough: cf. F. <ets>satire</ets>. See <er>Sate</er>,
<er>Sad</er>, <pos>a.</pos>, and cf. <er>Saturate</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>A composition, generally poetical, holding up vice or
folly to reprobation; a keen or severe exposure of what in public or
private morals deserves rebuke; an invective poem; <as>as, the
<ex>Satires</ex> of Juvenal</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Keenness and severity of remark; caustic exposure to
reprobation; trenchant wit; sarcasm.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Lampoon; sarcasm; irony; ridicule; pasquinade;
burlesque; wit; humor.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Satirical</ent>⟦br⟧
<ent>Satiric</ent>⟦br⟧
